In Robot.startDevice we have the following:

``` javascript
  var str = "Starting device '" + device.name + "'";

  if (device.pin) {
    str += " on pin " + device.pin;
  }
```

However, for devices connected to pin 0 (analog pin common on Arduinos), the log output doesn't say which pin number it is.

It should probably be something like this instead:

``` javascript
  var str = "Starting device '" + device.name + "'";

  if (device.pin || device.pin === 0) {
    str += " on pin " + device.pin;
  }
```

I'd be happy to provide a PR, if interested.

Hi, would you consider adding (or specifying) user modifiable field on devices for the purpose of storing non-standard properties?

I find myself adding extra functionality to some devices quite often (e.g. simple hold event handler on a button):

```
work: function (my) {
    var holdTime = 2000;
    var timeout = null;

    function holdHandler() {
      console.log("hold");
    }

    my.button.on("push", function () {
      console.log("push");
      timeout = setTimeout(holdHandler, holdTime);
    });

    my.button.on("release", function () {
      console.log("release");
      if (timeout && !timeout._called) {
        clearTimeout(timeout);
      }
    });
  }
```

It begs moving `holdTime` and `timeout` to the button:

```
devices: {
  button: {
    driver: "button",
    pin: 4,
    userProperties: {
      holdTime: 2000,
      timeout: null
    }
  }
}
```

I can do that right now and it works fine, but I don't really know if it's going to break something down the road.
So the idea is: you specify some field to users like "put your stuff in here" and similarly to module developers "hey don't touch this".

Does it make sense? It's about convention I guess.

