This PR extracts the existing Cylon API from core, into a new module (`cylon-api-http`).

This significantly slims down core, and allows for modular API usage going forward.

These space savings are particularly important for core, since any `cylon-*` module also needs to require its own copy of Cylon core.

With this change, users can also specify what API servers they'd like to use, rather than getting a Big Ball of Mud API server included by default.

The main corresponding change to the extracted API server is that it no longer tries to load Cylon directly, instead receiving `opts.mcp` in the constructor.
## Usage:

``` javascript
var Cylon = require("cylon");

// acts as existing, attempts to load `cylon-api-http` and create an instance
Cylon.api();

// attempts to load `cylon-api-http`, passes through the options object
Cylon.api({ https: false });

// attempts to load `cylon-api-ws`, passes through the options object if provided
Cylon.api("ws");
Cylon.api("ws", {});

// you can also directly pass in a constructor
var MQTT = require("cylon-api-mqtt");
Cylon.api(MQTT, { /* mqtt options */ });
```

e.g.

``` javascript
var Cylon = require("./");

Cylon.robot({
  connections: {
    loopback: {
      adaptor: "loopback",
      devices: {
        ping: { driver: "ping", pin: 1 }
      }
    }
  },

  work: function(my) {
    every((2).seconds(), function() {
      console.log(my.ping.ping());
    });
  }
}).start();
```

In the event of a name collision between the `devices` hash and a nested device, the nested device will 'win'.

Additionally, fixed a potential future bug in device/connection initialization if someone created a device/conn named `length`. Not sure why that would happen, but better safe than sorry.e.g.

``` javascript
var Cylon = require("./");

Cylon.robot({
  connections: {
    loopback: {
      adaptor: "loopback",
      devices: {
        ping: { driver: "ping", pin: 1 }
      }
    }
  },

  work: function(my) {
    every((2).seconds(), function() {
      console.log(my.ping.ping());
    });
  }
}).start();
```

In the event of a name collision between the `devices` hash and a nested device, the nested device will 'win'.

Additionally, fixed a potential future bug in device/connection initialization if someone created a device/conn named `length`. Not sure why that would happen, but better safe than sorry.

Adds the Lo-Dash utility module, to help ensure our iterators are consistent and simplify code where possible to prevent ambiguity.

A couple of gems:
- `_.map` can be used in the same matter as Ruby's Enumerable#map, but also allows for key fetching.
  This allows for the following code simplification:

``` javascript
var fns = [];

for (var bot in this.robots) {
  var robot = this.robots[bot];
  fns.push(robot.halt.bind(robot));
}

// becomes

var fns = _.map(this.robots, "halt");
```
- `_.forEach` iterates just as well over arrays as objects, meaning we don't have to keep track of prop/key assignment

``` javascript
var obj = {
  "TestBot": { start: function() {} },
  "NewBot": { start: function() {} }
};

_.forEach(obj, function(bot, name) {
  console.log(name);
  bot.start();
});

// calls #start() for each bot, and logs "TestBot" and "NewBot" to the console
```
- `_.invoke` calls a function on each value of a passed array or object.
  If a string is passed, it's assumed to be a function property.
  This simplifies the following code:

``` javascript
var devices = [],
    connections = [],
    n;

for (n in this.connections) {
  connections.push(this.connections[n].toJSON());
}

for (n in this.devices) {
  devices.push(this.devices[n].toJSON());
}

return {
  name: this.name,
  connections: connections,
  devices: devices,
  commands: Object.keys(this.commands)
};

// becomes

return {
  name: this.name,
  connections: _.invoke(this.connections, "toJSON"),
  devices: _.invoke(this.devices, "toJSON"),
  commands: _.keys(this.commands)
};
```
- `_.include/contains` is a simpler, easier to use presence checker for arrays than `Array#indexOf`

``` javascript
["robot", "name", "adaptor"].indexOf(opt) < 0;

// or

!!~["robot", "name", "adaptor"].indexOf(opt);

// becomes

_.contains(["robot", "name", "adaptor"], opt);
```
- `_.result` fetches a property from an object, returning the value directly if it's a primitive, or calling a function if one is found.
  I've [added it to the Robot constructor](https://github.com/hybridgroup/cylon/commit/c9e16fe8c220362d2f990d2e68f934f732fa64ef?diff=split), to simplify fetching of `opts.commands`

``` javascript
var object = {
  'alpha': 'hi there',
  'bravo': function() {
    return this.alpha;
  }
};

_.result(object, 'alpha');
// 'hi there'

_.result(object, 'bravo');
// 'hi there'
```

There's probably a few other places in Cylon this can be added (the API comes to mind) but I hope this nailed some of the more important parts.

The `lodash.js` file added in `lib/` will load the standard ES5-based version of Lo-Dash on most environments, and the backwards-compatible version for platforms like Tessel, which may not support all latest language features.

Other potentially useful functions can be found in the [Lo-Dash docs](https://lodash.com/docs).

Simple extraction out of Connection/Device initialization code inside Robot.

This yields an interesting boon, however - this is now a valid Cylon program:

``` javascript
var Cylon = require('cylon');

Cylon
  .robot()
  .connection({ name: 'loopback', adaptor: 'loopback' })
  .device({ name: 'ping', driver: 'ping' })
